commentText: Back in 2005-2006 when Craigslist was just starting to spread to other cities, I picked up gigs left and right - people were highballing you more than anything, because not too many workers knew about the site and there was a high demand for all kinds of labor. I - quite naively - thought this would keep up for at least a few years.   I still use the site these days, but no one can rely on it in the way you're describing here, especially in dense cities like NYC, LA, SF... if it's a general labor gig, you probably have under 10-20 minutes to respond before the job is taken, and even then, you're completing against dozens of people. Advertising your general services like you did is a complete waste of time when employers know they'll get hundreds of replies from desperate people. The number of people I've seen offering less than minimum wage for skilled labor is disgusting.

videoTitle: Top 5 mistakes to avoid when hiring an Auto Transport Company to Ship Your Car
videoDescription: We discuss the most common mistakes people make when hiring an auto transport company to haul their car across the country.
commentText: To all watching this video in August of 2022 or beyond :   Around the 8:00 mark where we discuss deposits  - Please understand we are describing the practices of a large % of the online slimy transport firms you will encounter out there. We are obviously not describing how we operate at https://airRyd.com - And the strategy described of "waiting to pay a deposit until a truck is assigned to the order " - simply no longer works because these large firms have adjusted, and they will often simply claim that a trucking company has been assigned, (even if they have not ) just to give justification to charge your card a nice $200-300 deposit fee. Then once your card has been charged, they'll update you a day or two later,  to let you know the "supposed" trucking company has unfortunately cancelled. But they now have you locked in all the same, and you have no way of ever knowing what's what. Some companies also even have shell trucking companies with real DOT #s on standby, with an actual person on the other end of the phone, just so they can claim they have dispatched out your order - so they can then charge your card. It is a tough world out there for the unknowing consumer.   At our firm, over at airRyd - we always have the same exact process on every single order. We charge a flat $89 (open transport order / per car ) or a flat $125 (enclosed transport order / per car ) on EVERY single order. It never changes. No games are ever played. Nothing beyond that is ever due until the delivery at the destination when your car is dropped off to you.  And if your asking, why charge an upfront fee ? We have a couple very clear answers to that question.   1.) If we charged nothing when a customer booked an order, we would have no possible way of knowing what orders are real, what orders are fake or spam, and we would have absolutely no way of knowing if this customer will be MIA or unresponsive once we do locate an option to get the car moved. This takes real human capital to deliver a good service, we can't possibly devote hundreds of hours to orders that simply are never happening. It is just a way to weed out those who are serious from those who are simply shopping.  2.) If we actually posted hundreds of "non-confirmed " orders on major load boards, including our own at airRyd.com - trucks will eventually realize when they inquire in on these loads, that at least 50% are not even legitimate. This will lead to a drop in activity from trucking companies, and thus make our real orders much harder to move. Trucks don't have time to waste, they want to deal with companies that have LEGITIMATE loads, not "maybe" loads. So this would lead to a damaged reputation for us on all major load boards.  3.) There is simply no incentive from our perspective to deliver a good service to a customer with a big question mark over their order, and there is also basically no trust from the customer perspective if they are not willing to pay a small fee to hire us. So the order is not on the right footing when no monies have been paid.  For these reasons and others, this is why we operate as we do. And if anyone is truly unhappy at anytime with our services, we will happily refund them on the booking fee , no questions asked.  To book an order with us today, please visit us online at https://airRyd.com  - or shoot us a text to our quote hotline at 913-215-3113  THANKS TO ALL !!! : )  Wes - with ATD

commentText: It's so different the way the US do their degree/intake/course/clinical and how the new grad application process and year is. I'm in my 3rd and FINAL year of nursing in Australia, NSW and we have 1 chance at the public health system for new grad and if we don't get it that's it we can't apply later it's you apply in July for the following years intake and there's no need for letters of recommendation, having a job already in the industry isn't much of an advantage unless you know someone high up and they love you or you have family there already. there were 600 people interviewed in my area  (my area is rediculously too big), not including the skype calls or interviews in another city and there are only 218 positions. at the hospital I want there's 69! And yet at my uni theres 1400 students! kinda messed up really huh. Oh and we don't have a NCLEX once we finish our degree we can get a job and get marked off all over again ugh!!! We also have rotations through wards so 6 months in 1 ward and 6 in another and sometimes we don't get a choice. we can put in preferences but that's it. With all that said I'm super keen to start nursing :D
